        <abstract> 
<p>Discusses the mimicry of the <hi rend="italic">Volucella</hi> flies, and the bees and wasps they mimic. Compares it with the different object of mimicry in butterflies.</p>  
<p>Refers to incompleteness of Cuthbert Collingwood’s paper [? "On homophormism, or organic representative forms", <hi rend="italic">Proc. Liverpool Lit. &amp; Philos. Soc.</hi> 14 (1860): 181–216].</p>  
<p>Thanks CD for help in selecting a publisher for his book [<hi rend="italic">The naturalist on the river Amazons</hi> (1863)].</p> 
        </abstract>
